Image:The Fabs.JPG|thumb|The Beatles have topped the UK Albums Chart with fifteen different albums and spent 174 weeks at number one, longer than any other artist.
The UK Albums Chart is a weekly record chart based on album sales from Friday to Thursday in the United Kingdom (the chart week ran from Sunday to Saturday until 2015). It listed only compact disc|physical album sales until 2007, after which it has also included albums sold Digital distribution|digitally, and from March 2015, includes streamed tracks. The chart is currently compiled by the Official Charts Company (OCC) on behalf of the UK music industry,<ref>Cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/the-charts-we-compile/|title=The Charts We Compile|publisher=Official Charts Company|location=London|year=2010|accessdate=28 June 2011</ref> and each week's new number one is first announced on Friday evenings (Sunday evenings until July 2015) by BBC Radio 1 on The Official Chart|their weekly chart show.<ref>cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/chart/albums|title=The Official UK Top 40 Albums Chart|year=2011|publisher=BBC Radio 1|location=London|accessdate=28 June 2011</ref>

The album chart was first published by ''Record Mirror'' on 28 July 1956<ref>cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/album_chart_history_1956.php|title=1956|first=Sharon|last=Mawer|year=2008|publisher=Official Charts Company|location=London|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308002257/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/album_chart_history_1956.php|archivedate=8 March 2009|deadurl=yes|accessdate=28 June 2011</ref>—the album at number one that week was ''Songs for Swingin' Lovers!'' by Frank Sinatra.<ref>cite web|url=http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-5648403/Albums-chart-50-chart-facts.html|title=Albums chart: 50 chart facts.|date=5 August 2006|publisher=''Music Week''|location=London|issn=0265-1548|oclc=60620772|accessdate=15 July 2011|quote=...&nbsp;The first number one album – Songs For Swingin' Lovers by Frank Sinatra&nbsp;...</ref> As of|2013|11|24, 1,000 different albums have reached the top of the chart;<ref>cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25079172 |title=Robbie Williams scores UK's 1,000th number one album|work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=24 November 2013 |accessdate=23 September 2015</ref> 12 artists have topped the chart with nine or more different albums. The most successful act is The Beatles, who have reached number one with fifteen records and spent 174 weeks at the top, longer than any other artist.<ref>cite news|title=The Fab Four to perform Beatles tribute at sports complex|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-130EB623DC712890.html|newspaper=Naperville Sun|publisher=NewsBank|location=Naperville, Illinois|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010|quote=...&nbsp;The Beatles have had more No. 1 albums (15) on the United Kingdom charts and held down the top spot longer (174 weeks) than any other musical act.&nbsp;...</ref> Elvis Presley is the most successful solo artist with 13 number-one albums, while Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna is the most successful female artist with 12 number-one albums in the UK.

Artists
The following artists have been credited on at least nine different number one albums, as recognised by the OCC. Appearances on compilation albums featuring various artists are not included.
